questiontext.text:
Surface integrals involving vectors


The unit normal

For the surface of any three-dimensional shape, it is possible to find a vector lying perpendicular to the surface and with magnitude 1. The unit vector points outwards from a closed surface and is usually denoted by \(\underline{\hat{n}}\).

Example

If \(S\) is the surface of the sphere \(x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = a^2\) find the unit normal \(\underline{\hat{n}}\).

Solution

The unit normal at the point \(P(x,y,z)\) points away from the centre of the sphere i.e. it lies in the direction of \(x \underline{i} + y \underline{j} + z\underline{k}\). To make this a unit vector it must be divided by its magnitude \(\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}\) i.e. the unit vector is \begin{eqnarray*}\underline{\hat{n}} &=& \dfrac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}\underline{i}+ \dfrac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}\underline{j}+\dfrac{z}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}\underline{k}\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad \\\\&=& \dfrac{x}{a}\underline{i} + \dfrac{y}{a}\underline{j} + \dfrac{z}{a}\underline{k}\end{eqnarray*} where \(a=\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}\)\quad is the radius of the sphere.

Example

For the cube \(0 \le x \le 1\), \(0 \le y \le 1\), \(0 \le z \le 1\), find the unit outward normal \(\underline{\hat{n}}\) for each face.

Solution

On the face given by \(x=0\), the unit normal points in the negative \(x\)-direction. Hence the unit normal is \(- \underline{i}\). Similarly :-

On the face \(x=1\) the unit normal is \(\underline{i}\). \qquad On the face \(y=0\) the unit normal is \(-\underline{j}\).

On the face \(y=1\) the unit normal is \(\underline{j}\). \qquad On the face \(z=0\) the unit normal is \(-\underline{k}\).

On the face \(z=1\) the unit normal is \(\underline{k}\).


\(\underline{dS}\) and the unit normal

The vector \(\underline{dS}\) is a vector, being an element of the surface with magnitude \(du\,dv\) and direction perpendicular to the surface.
If the plane in question is the \(Oxy\) plane, then \(\underline{dS} = \underline{\hat{n}}\, du\, dv = \underline{k}\, dx\, dy\).

If the plane in question is not one of the three coordinate planes (\(Oxy\), \(Oxz\), \(Oyz\)), appropriate adjustments must be made to express \(\underline{dS}\) in terms of two of \(dx\) and \(dy\) and \(dz\).

Example

The rectangle \(OABC\) lies in the plane \(z = y\) (Figure 8).

The vertices are \(O = (0,0,0)\), \(A = (1,0,0)\), \(B = (1,1,1)\) and \(C = (0,1,1)\).

Find a unit vector \(\underline{\hat{n}}\) normal to the plane and an appropriate vector \(\underline{dS}\) expressed in terms of \(dx\) and \(dy\).

Solution

Note that two vectors in the rectangle are \({\overrightarrow {OA}}=\underline{i}\) and \({\overrightarrow {OC}}=\underline{j} + \underline{k}\). A vector perpendicular to the plane is \(\underline{i} \times (\underline{j} + \underline{k}) = -\underline{j} + \underline{k}\). However, this vector is of magnitude \(\sqrt{2}\) so the unit normal vector is \(\underline{\hat{n}} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(-\underline{j} + \underline{k}) = -\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\underline{j} + \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\underline{k}\). The vector \(\underline{dS}\) is therefore \((-\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\underline{j} + \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\underline{k})\, du\, dv\) where \(du\) and \(dv\) are increments in the plane of the rectangle \(OABC\). Now, one increment, say \(du\), may point in the \(x\)-direction while \(dv\) will point in a direction up the plane, parallel to \(OC\). Thus \(du = dx\) and (by Pythagoras) \(dv = \sqrt{(dy)^2 + (dz)^2}\). However, as \(z = y\), \(dz = dy\) and hence \(dv = \sqrt{2} dy\).

Thus, \(\underline{dS} = (-\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\underline{j} + \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\underline{k})\, dx\, \sqrt{2}\, dy = (-\underline{j} + \underline{k}) \,dx\, dy\). Note :- the factor of \(\sqrt{2}\) could also have been found by comparing the area of rectangle \(OABC\), i.e. \(1\), with the area of its projection in the \(Oxy\) plane i.e. \(OADE\) with area \(\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\).

Integrating a scalar field

A function can be integrated over a surface by constructing a double integral and integrating in a manner similar to that shown in 27.1 and 27.2. Often, such integrals can be carried out with respect to an element containing the unit normal.

Example

Evaluate the integral \[\displaystyle\int_A \dfrac{1}{1+x^2}\; \underline{dS}\] over the area \(A\) where \(A\) is the square \(0 \le x \le 1\), \(0 \le y \le 1\), \(z=0\).

Solution

In this integral, \(\underline{dS}\) becomes \(\underline{k}\, dx\, dy\) i.e. the unit normal times the surface element. Thus the integral is \begin{eqnarray*} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \displaystyle\int_{x=0}^1 \dfrac{\underline{k}}{1+x^2} \, dx\, dy &=& \underline{k}\displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \left[\phantom{\dfrac{}{}} \tan^{-1} x \right]_0^1 dy \\ &=&\underline{k} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \left[ (\frac{\pi}{4}-0) \right]_0^1 dy = \frac{\pi}{4} \underline{k} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 dy\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad \\ &=& \frac{\pi}{4} \underline{k} \end{eqnarray*}

Example

Find \(\displaystyle\int\!\!\int_S u \;\underline{dS}\) where \(u = x^2 + y^2 + z^2\) and \(S\) is the surface of the unit cube\(0 \le x \le 1\), \(0 \le y \le 1\), \(0 \le z \le 1\).

Solution

The unit cube has six faces and the unit normal vector \(\underline{\hat{n}}\) points in a different direction on each face; see Example 18. The surface integral must be evaluated for each face separately and the results summed.

On the face \(x = 0\), the unit normal \(\underline{\hat{n}} = -\underline{i}\) and the surface integral is \begin{eqnarray*} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \displaystyle\int_{z=0}^1 (0^2 + y^2 + z^2)(-\underline{i}) dz dy &=& -\underline{i} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \left[ y^2 z + \frac{1}{3} z^3 \right]_{z=0}^1 dy \\ &=& -\underline{i} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \left( y^2 + \frac{1}{3} \right) dy = -\underline{i} \left[ \frac{1}{3}y^3 + \frac{1}{3}y \right]_0^1 = - \frac{2}{3}\underline{i} \end{eqnarray*} On the face \(x = 1\), the unit normal \(\underline{\hat{n}} = \underline{i}\) and the surface integral is \begin{eqnarray*} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \displaystyle\int_{z=0}^1 (1^2 + y^2 + z^2)(\underline{i}) dz dy &=& \underline{i} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \left[ z + y^2 z + \frac{1}{3} z^3 \right]_{z=0}^1 dy \\ &=& \underline{i} \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^1 \left( y^2 + \frac{4}{3} \right) dy = \underline{i} \left[ \frac{1}{3}y^3 + \frac{4}{3}y \right]_0^1 = \frac{5}{3}\underline{i} \end{eqnarray*} The net contribution from the faces \(x = 0\) and \(x = 1\) is \(-\frac{2}{3}\underline{i} + \frac{5}{3}\underline{i} = \underline{i}\).

Due to the symmetry of the scalar field \(u\) and the unit cube, the net contribution from the faces \(y=0\) and \(y=1\) is \(\underline{j}\) while the net contribution from the faces \(z=0\) and \(z=1\) is \(\underline{k}\).

Adding, we obtain \( \displaystyle\int\!\!\int_S u \underline{dS} = \underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k}\)


Key Point

A scalar function integrated with respect to a normal vector \(\underline{dS}\) gives a vector quantity. When the surface does not lie in one of the planes \(Oxy\), \(Oxz\), \(Oyz\), extra care must be taken when finding \(\underline{dS}\).


Example

Find \(\displaystyle\int\!\!\int_S ({\underline \nabla} \cdot \underline{F}) \underline{dS}\) where \(\underline{F} = 2x \underline{i} + y z \underline{j} + x y \underline{k}\) and \(S\) is the surface of the triangle with vertices at \((0,0,0)\), \((1,0,0)\) and \((1,1,0)\).

Solution

Note that \({\underline \nabla} \cdot \underline{F} = 2 + z = 2\) as \(z = 0\) everywhere along \(S\). As the triangle lies in the \(Oxy\) plane, the normal vector \(\underline{n} = \underline{k}\) and \(\underline{dS} = \underline{k} dy dx\).

Thus, \(\qquad\displaystyle \displaystyle\int\!\!\int_S ({\underline \nabla} \cdot \underline{F}) \underline{dS} = \displaystyle\int_{x=0}^1 \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^x 2 dy dx {\underline k}= \displaystyle\int_0^1 \left[\phantom{\dfrac{1}{1}}\!\!\!2y\right]_0^x dx{\underline k} = \displaystyle\int_0^1 2x dx{\underline k} = \left[\phantom{\dfrac{}{}}x^2\right]_0^1 \underline{k}= {\underline k}\)

Example

Find \(\displaystyle\int\!\!\int_S f \;\underline{dS}\) where \(f\) is the function \(2x\) and \(S\) is the surface of the trianglebounded by \((0,0,0)\), \((0,1,1)\) and \((1,0,1)\). (See Figure 9.)

Solution

The unit vector \(\underline{n}\) is perpendicular to two vectors in the plane e.g. \((\underline{j}+\underline{k})\) and \((\underline{i}+\underline{k})\). The vector \((\underline{j}+\underline{k}) \times (\underline{i}+\underline{k}) = \underline{i} + \underline{j} - \underline{k} \) which has magnitude \(\sqrt{3}\). Hence the unit normal vector \(\hat{{\underline n}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\underline{i}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\underline{j}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\underline{k}\).

As the area of the triangle \(S\) is \(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\) and the area of its projection in the \(Oxy\) plane is \(\frac{1}{2}\), the vector \(\underline{dS} = \dfrac{\sqrt{3}/2}{1/2}\hat{{\underline n}}\; dy dx = (\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k}) dy dx \).

Thus \begin{eqnarray*} \displaystyle\int\!\!\int_S f \underline{dS} &=& (\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k}) \displaystyle\int_{x=0}^1 \displaystyle\int_{y=0}^{1-x} 2x\; dy dx \\ &=& (\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k})\displaystyle\int_{x=0}^1 \left[\phantom{\dfrac{1}{1}}\!\!\! 2xy \right]_{y=0}^{1-x} dx \\ &=&(\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k}) \displaystyle\int_{x=0}^1 (2x - 2x^2) dx \\ &=&(\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k}) \left[ x^2 - \frac{2}{3}x^3 \right]_0^1 = \frac{1}{3}(\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k})\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad \\ \end{eqnarray*}
